  "input": "Hospitalization report \n\n               The child SAIDANI Mohamed Seif Eddine, aged 7 years and 5 months; originally from and residing in Oran, followed in our department since the age of 11 months for post-measles COPD and primary immunodeficiency type \"Agammaglobulinemia\" with severe neutropenia admitted to our level for treatment of immunoglobulin N 75 and for exploration and management of vomiting and chronic abdominal pain. History:\nFamily:\n-Father: 32 years old, O positive, smoker\n-Mother: 32 years old, A positive, dermatological lesions not documented\n-Siblings: 1-Boy 11 years old, eczema, screening done (negative). Personal:\nPhysiological:\nPoorly monitored pregnancy, delivery 36 weeks by upper route indicated: for closed cervix\nNeonatal resuscitation: present. Apgar not mentioned in the health record. Birth weight: 03 kg 300\nExclusive maternal breastfeeding\nAnti-rachitis prophylaxis received at the age of 1 month and 6 months\nVaccination: vaccination delay\nPsychomotor development: judged good\nAcademic performance: average\nPersonal atopy: no\nPathological:\nNeonatal period:\n-Neonatal jaundice put on phototherapy. - Hospitalized for 07 days in the neonatal period for early respiratory distress and late prematurity of 36 weeks having benefited from antibiotic therapy. -At the age of 1 and a half months: Severe bronchiolitis\n- Age of 02 and a half months: Measles complicated by pneumonia. History of illness:\nMain diagnosis: DIP agammaglobulinemia type. Associated diagnoses: Post-measles COPD. Date of diagnosis: 09/16/2019. Age of diagnosis: 11 months. Diagnostic elements:\nClinic:\nBronchial congestion from birth\nMeasles at the age of 2 months complicated by measles pneumonia. Organic:\nImmune assessment 07/21/2019 EHU\nIgA<0.2 g/L 6 to 12 months (0.13-0.82)\nIgG1 1.65 g/L 1-1 and ½ (2.5-8.2)\nIgG2 < 0.2g/L 1-1 and ½ (0.38-2.4)\nIgG 4 < 0.03 g/L 1-1 and ½ (<0.03-0.62)\nImmune assessment at Béni Messous hospital (06/10/20)\nIgG=12.07g/l IgA=less than 0.02g/l IgM=0.19g/L\nAbsence of LB with profound reduction of NK. Normal intracytoplasmic expression of the Btk gene in monocytes in the patient and his mother compared to a control subject. The diagnosis in favor of congenital Agammaglobulinemia associated with severe neutropenia, The association of severe neutropenia with congenital agammaglobulinemia linked to X \"Bruton's disease\" is often described in the literature. Radiological:\nFront chest x-ray: (07/14/2019): left pericardial opacity with bilateral infiltrate\nCervico-thoracic CT (01/15/2019) clinical “Benserai”: objectifying:\nDiscreet thickening of the ary-epiglottic folds more marked on the right without associated cervical anomaly, Reticular infiltrate with right hilo-apical alveolar condensation\nProcessing in progress:\nItraconazole: 5 mg/kg/day\nBactrim 400mg/80mg/day\nTwice-daily physiotherapy\nBudecort 200ug 2 */D\nRepercussions of the illness and clarification:\nNutritionally:\nFailure to thrive: Weight: 17kg (-2.2DS) Height: 123 cm (+0.1DS). Moderate to severe malnutrition: Gomez: 72% Waterloo: 75% Moderate underweight\nNutritional assessment: 24/23/2026: protein-energy malnutrition\nOn the pulmonary level:\nNo signs of chronic respiratory failure. ECBC: 02/28/2026: No germ\nEFR 16/12/24: within the limits of the standard. Gait test: without abnormality, no desaturation or dyspnea on exertion after 6 minutes. Thoracic CT 02/24/2026: Unremarkable examination\nOn the infectious level:\n*Skin: no cutaneous or mucosal mycoses and no skin infections. *Digestive: Chronic abdominal pain with vomiting\nAbdominal CT 02/26/2026: Cecal ileocolitis with an inflammatory/infectious appearance\nOn the cardiac level:\nB1B2 audible, no added noise or hiss, HR: 88 b/min\nAbsence of signs of chronic cor pulmonale\nCardiac Doppler ultrasound 11/21/2024: Within normal limits. Intermediate history: since the last visit 01/24/2026\nSeveral consultations at the Canastel UMC level for abdominal pain and vomiting benefiting from symptomatic treatment\nHISTORY OF ILLNESS in relation to the reason for hospitalization: 02/23/2026\nGoes back 3 months previously with the gradual onset of abdominal pain;\nvomiting motivating the mother consulted HDJ pulmonology or an abdominopelvic ultrasound done returning without anomaly supplemented by a FOGD + biopsy showing HP gastritis. A gastropediatric opinion was requested, the child was put on triple therapy but given the lack of clinical improvement and the appearance of weight loss with deterioration in general condition, the child was hospitalized for further exploration and treatment.\nClinical examination at admission: 02/23/2026\nAnthropometric measurements:\nWeight: 17kg (-2.2 DS) Height: 123 cm (+0.1 DS) BMI: 11.2kg (-2.9 DS) Severe weight loss\nP/A: 72% Moderate underweight P/T: 75% Moderate thinness\n- Average general condition, afebrile, integuments and conjunctiva pals\nPleuropulmonary examination: eupneic, FR: 20 cycles/min, No signs of respiratory distress, SaO2: 98%, Clear auscultation in both lung fields\nCardiovascular examination: HR: 122 b/min, CRT < 3 sec, Auscultation: B1, B2 audible properties, absence of added noises\nAbdominopelvic examination: Soft abdomen, no organomegaly, free hernia orifices, preserved transit, early vomiting of food\nENT: clean throat\nReview of other devices: Is unremarkable\nWhat to do:\n-Hospitalization\n-Condition, peripheral venous route\n- Immunoglobulin infusion at a rate of 0.8g/kg to be administered over 4 hours\n-Double antibiotic therapy: claforan and flagyl\n-Dietician advice: put the child on oliclinomel\n-Complete biological assessment\n-Plan an abdominopelvic ultrasound or abdominal CT\nAdmission assessment: 02/23/2026\nSNF:\nGB: 1870 elements PNN: 770Lymph760 i.e. leuko-neutro-lymphopenia\nHb: 11.5g/dl VGM: 98.2fl CCMH: 32.2 g/dl\nPlatelet: 238,000 elements TP: 90.2% TCK: 37 SecFibrinogene: 3.2 g/l\nFSP: Leukocytes: Leukopenia 1870, PNN: 780 G/L Lympho: 820 G/L\nPlatelets: Very rich in platelets, predominance of microthrombocytes, presence of a few large or even giant platelets, presence of small platelet aggregates\nErythrocytes: Anisocytosis with a macrocytic tendency, presence of a few schistocytes,\nPresence of 4% of suspicious cells\nBlood ionogram: Na 130 K: 3.84 Cl: 95\nUrea: 0.14g/lCreat: 3.98mg/l\nAST: 24.5 ALT: 9.5\ngGT: 10.32 TG: 1.06 g/l Cholesterol: 0.92\nAlbumin: 30g/l Uric acid: 9.29\nAbdominopelvic ultrasound: without abnormality\nThoraco-abdomino-pelvic CT: cecal ileocolitis with an inflammatory or infectious appearance\nStool coproparasitology: negative\nQuantify: positive\nBK PCR: negative\nGastric tubing looking for BK: negative direct examination\nAutoimmunity assessment: in progress\nCAT: given the results of the abdominopelvic CT and will quantify it as positive:\n- Patient presented to the gastropediatrics department in Canastel for a possible colonoscopy + biopsy, but patient refused given the absence of a probe adapted to his age and weight\n- anti-tuberculosis treatment was started on day 9 of hospitalization based on 2RHZE/4RH\nEvolution:\nDuring his hospitalization\nClinically:\n-a weight gain of 1KG\n-disappearance of vomiting but persistence of abdominal pain\nOn the paraclinical level:\nFNS with FS: GB: 2266 PNN: 540 LYM: 1620 i.e. leuko-neutropenia\nFSP: Significant anisopoikilocytosis, presence of macrocytes, numerous schistocytes, a few target cells\nPlq: rich with numerous platelet aggregates\nA hematology opinion made: indication of PMO but patient refused by the intensive care team\nThe patient is discharged on 03/19/2026 with a check-up appointment on 03/23/2026 with letter for colonoscopy with biopsy. To do and collect:\n-Recovers the autoimmunity assessment\n-Retrieves the results of the immunodeficiency assessment of the patient and the mother\n- Retrieve gastric tube results\n-Do the colonoscopy + biopsy\n-Represent the patient to hematology for a marrow puncture.",
